licate photos. Select them all and delete them in one shot. While you’re at it, delete the forwarded photos and picture messages you don’t really need too.\r\n<ol start="3">\r\n 	<li><u>Change default Camera resolution</u></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nDid you know the photos you take with your high-resolution phone camera occupy a few MBs of storage space each? This is ‘n’ times the space occupied by a forwarded photo. So even if you have just 20 photos taken in high-resolution stored on your phone camera that can mean you’re dedicating a few GBs of your space to those 20 photos. Think about it; are those photos really worth it? If not, delete them and also go to your camera settings and update the default photo quality your camera to save small sized photos.\r\n<ol start="4">\r\n 	<li><u>Off-load photos and documents</u></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nIf it’s been more than a fortnight you did this, immediately connect your phone to your laptop and move all important data like photos, emails, and downloaded documents from it to the laptop. That’s also a great way to backup your data safely. Repeat this exercise whenever possible to avoid unnecessary data clutter on your phone.\r\n<ol start="5">\r\n 	<li><u>Delete Unnecessary Games &amp; Apps</u></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nOkay there has to be some deleting after all. All of us have at least 1 or 2 apps we downloaded a few months or maybe a year back but haven’t used in ages. Well, it’s time to bid adieu to them. A lot of games save a ton of metadata on your phone and if you aren’t playing them, why keep all that data stored unnecessarily? Delete old unused apps and games. <u>Bonus Tip</u> – Navigate to your app storage section in Settings and checkout the amount of data each app saves on your phone. If you don’t use something daily, clear its data and cache to squeeze out every bit of space it is taking up.\r\n<ol start="6">\r\n 	<li><u>Clear your browser Cache</u></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nChrome or Safari, all browsers save web history and data you simply don’t need. Go to your phone’s Settings and open up your browser app. Scroll down to find an option to “Clear History and Website Data” or “Clear Browsing Data” to remove junk from your phone. This should ease up things a lot.\r\n<ol start="7">\r\n 	<li><u>Update your phone’s OS</u></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nHave you been ignoring the flash for an OS upgrade for too long? If yes, stop doing that immediately since updating the OS can in-fact set a lot of things straight. It internally performs a sort of sweep of old data and refreshes system files to store only the new data. So it’s a great way to get things into shape on your phone. Upgrade your OS and experience the difference.\r\n\r\n<strong>Recap of lessons learnt</strong>\r\n\r\nThe list of easy ways to free up phone storage doesn’t end there. You can also do stuff like delete old message chains, chat histories, chose the setting to never save messages and photos for more than a week, stop using apps like Photo Stream, etc. to keep tabs on increasing storage clutter. But all of this will be of no use if you make errors like saving duplicate photos and never off-loading your phone data. So clean up your phone regularly and keep backing it up to always have all the space you want at hand!', 'Allow your phone to breathe with these 7 tricks to free up storage', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '512-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-01-05 10:46:19', '2018-01-05 10:46:19', '', 512, 'http://pcgarage.uk.com/blog/512-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
