 why keep all that data stored unnecessarily? Delete old unused apps and games. <u>Bonus Tip</u> – Navigate to your app storage section in Settings and checkout the amount of data each app saves on your phone. If you don’t use something daily, clear its data and cache to squeeze out every bit of space it is taking up.\r\n<ol start="6">\r\n 	<li><strong>Clear your browser Cache</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nChrome or Safari, all browsers save web history and data you simply don’t need. Go to your phone’s Settings and open up your browser app. Scroll down to find an option to “Clear History and Website Data” or “Clear Browsing Data” to remove junk from your phone. This should ease up things a lot.\r\n<ol start="7">\r\n 	<li><strong>Update your phone’s OS</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nHave you been ignoring the flash for an OS upgrade for too long? If yes, stop doing that immediately since updating the OS can in-fact set a lot of things straight. It internally performs a sort of sweep of old data and refreshes system files to store only the new data. So it’s a great way to get things into shape on your phone. Upgrade your OS and experience the difference.\r\n\r\n<strong>Recap of lessons learnt</strong>\r\n\r\nThe list of easy ways to free up phone storage doesn’t end there. You can also do stuff like delete old message chains, chat histories, chose the setting to never save messages and photos for more than a week, stop using apps like Photo Stream, etc. to keep tabs on increasing storage clutter. But all of this will be of no use if you make errors like saving duplicate photos and never off-loading your phone data. So clean up your phone regularly and keep backing it up to always have all the space you want at hand!', 'Allow your phone to breathe with these 7 tricks to free up storage', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '512-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-01-05 11:07:10', '2018-01-05 11:07:10', '', 512, 'http://pcgarage.uk.com/blog/512-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
