(528, 1, '2018-01-05 11:24:29', '2018-01-05 11:24:29', 'There’s nothing more annoying than trying to capture a rare moment with your phone’s camera but having to deal with a hanging camera app due to low phone storage. Equally irritating are times where when trying to download an important work-related PDF document on the phone you are confronted with a message that says, “Phone Storage Full, Cannot Download”.\r\n\r\nRegardless of how much storage one opts for when buying a new phone, sooner or later the dreaded “Low Storage” message crops up on every phone screen. And when that happens you should gear up for app crashes, phone freezes, and inability to work with pretty much anything on your phone.\r\n\r\nSo does the solution lie in frantically deleting every message, chat, and picture on your phone? Or is a storage upgrade the last resort? Well actually there are neater workarounds to the problem. Read on to discover 7 cool ways to free up critical phone storage while making sure you don’t have to give up on chat histories and cute pictures / videos or invest in external storage accessories.\r\n\r\n<strong>Get the most out of every MB of storage on your phone with these 7 tips</strong>\r\n<h4><strong><img class="size-full wp-image-519 alignright" src="http://pcgarage.uk.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/Find-out-which-apps-are-the.jpg" alt="Find out which apps are the bulkiest" width="245" height="220" />1. Find out which apps are the bulkiest</strong></h4>\r\nThis may sound technical but it is actually one of the simplest hacks to free up phone storage. On your phone, go to Settings and navigate to the Storage section (On Android, this should be the Apps section). Here you will be able to see a list of installed apps arranged by the space they take up; so the ones at the top are eating away the largest chunks of your phone storage. If you don’t <em>really</em> need them, delete such apps. You can always download them again when needed.<strong><img class="wp-image-524 size-full alignright" src="http://pcgarage.uk.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/Delete-duplicate-photos-files-1.jpg" alt="Delete duplicate photos files" width="195" height="250" /></strong>\r\n<h4><strong>2. Delete duplicate photos</strong></h4>\r\nThe vice in forwarding is that the same picture message keeps floating from phone to phone over and over again. Go to your phone’s gallery and spot all duplicate photos. Select them all and delete them in one shot. While you’re at it, delete the forwarded photos and picture messages you don’t really need too.\r\n<h4><strong>3. Change default Camera resolution</strong></h4>\r\n<img class="size-full wp-image-527 alignright" src="http://pcgarage.uk.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/Change-default-Camera-resol.jpg" alt="Change default Camera resolution" width="300" height="200" />Did you know the photos you take with your high-resolution phone camera occupy a few MBs of storage space each? This is ‘n’ times the space occupied by a forwarded photo. So even if you have just 20 photos taken in high-resolution stored on your phone camera that can mean you’re dedicating a few GBs of your space to those 20 photos. Think about it; are those photos really worth it? If not, delete them and also go to your camera settings and update the default photo quality your camera to save small sized photos.\r\n<h4><strong>4. Off-load photos and documents</strong></h4>\r\nIf it’s been more than a fortnight you did this, immediately connect your phone to your laptop and move all important data like photos, emails, and downloaded documents from it to the laptop. That’s also a great way to backup your data safely. Repeat this exercise whenever possible to avoid unnecessary data clutter on your phone.\r\n<h4><strong>5. Delete Unnecessary Games &amp; Apps</strong></h4>\r\nOkay there has to be some deleting after all. All of us have at least 1 or 2 apps we downloaded a few months or maybe a year back but haven’t used in ages. Well, it’s time to bid adieu to them. A lot of games save a ton of metadata on your phone and if you aren’t playing them, why keep all that data stored unnecessarily? Delete old unused apps and games. <u>Bonus Tip</u> – Navigate to your app storage section in Settings and checkout the amount of data each app saves on your phone. If you don’t use something daily, clear its data and cache to squeeze out every bit of space it is taking up.\r\n<h4><strong>6. Clear your browser Cache</strong></h4>\r\nChrome or Safari, all browsers save web history and data you simply don’t need. Go to your phone’s Settings and open up your browser app. Scroll down to find an option to “Clear History and Website Data” or “Clear Browsing Data” to remove junk from your phone. This should ease up things a lot.\r\n<h4><strong>7. Update your phone’s OS</strong></h4>\r\nHave you been ignoring the flash for an OS upgrade for too long? If yes, stop doing that immediately since updating the OS can in-fact set a lot of things straight. It internally performs a sort of sweep of old data and refreshes system files to store only the new data. So it’s a great way to get things into shape on your phone. Upgrade your OS and experience the difference.\r\n\r\n<strong>Recap of lessons learnt</strong>\r\n\r\nThe list of easy ways to free up phone storage doesn’t end there. You can also do stuff like delete old message chains, chat histories, chose the setting to never save messages and photos for more than a week, stop using apps like Photo Stream, etc. to keep tabs on increasing storage clutter. But all of this will be of no use if you make errors like saving duplicate photos and never off-loading your phone data. So clean up your phone regularly and keep backing it up to always have all the space you want at hand!', 'Allow your phone to breathe with these 7 tricks to free up storage', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '512-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-01-05 11:24:29', '2018-01-05 11:24:29', '', 512, 'http://pcgarage.uk.com/blog/512-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
